			"byline" : "Nick Sambides Jr.",
			"background" : "img/_11036873.JPG",
			"description" : "The impact of the <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/07/06/news/state/explosions-erupt-from-derailed-train-carrying-petroleum-products-in-quebec/'>runaway train that crashed</a> into the small Canadian lakeside town of Lac Megantic, Quebec, on July 6, killing 47 people, rippled through the railway industry of Maine. The <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/10/09/business/lac-megantic-inspired-maine-rail-review-finds-safety-adequate/'>inspections of Maine’s railway system</a> ordered by Gov. Paul LePage and the Federal Railroad Administration in the days after the rail disaster unearthed <a href='http://www.maine.gov/mdot/railsafetyreport/'>no significant safety flaws</a> in the state’s 1,150-mile system. But the ripple effects of the accident swamped Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway, a Hermon-based company that lost a total of 28 workers to layoffs between U.S. and Canadian operations after its train exploded. The <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/08/07/business/railway-involved-in-quebec-crash-that-killed-47-files-for-bankruptcy/'>railway declared bankruptcy</a> and is <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/12/13/business/wall-street-investment-firm-emerges-as-potential-buyer-of-montreal-maine-and-atlantic-railway/'>now for sale</a>. Meanwhile, people whose livelihoods were dependent on the railway are <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/09/18/news/piscataquis/milo-area-businesses-feel-pain-as-bankrupt-railroad-struggles-to-survive/'>left facing an uncertain future</a>."
