			"background" : "img/LASTMINUTE_11875083.JPG",
			"description" : "<p>Four years after the Great Recession officially ended, Maine&rsquo;s economy in 2013 continued its slow slog to recovery. By most accounts, it was a good year, though<a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/10/25/politics/maine-economy-rebounding-slowly-but-national-events-make-predictions-a-guessing-game-experts-say/'> experts still suspect Maine&rsquo;s economy will recover more slowly than the nation&rsquo;s</a>. Employment is up. <a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/10/21/business/maine-homes-sales-jump-nearly-25-percent-in-september'>Home sales are up</a>.<a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/11/13/politics/maine-state-revenues-rise-but-finance-chief-warns-that-federal-shutdown-tax-hikes-could-quickly-darken-picture'> Tax collections are rising</a>. Maine&rsquo;s unemployment rate continually hit five-year lows all year,<a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/11/22/business/as-maines-unemployment-rate-dips-4000-face-loss-of-unemployment-benefits'> reaching a preliminary estimate of 6.7 percent in October</a>, the lowest since November 2008. The state lost 29,000 jobs in the Great Recession, and while there&rsquo;s still a ways to re-scale that peak,<a href='http://bangordailynews.com/2013/11/13/business/economist-maine-adding-jobs-but-wont-recover-from-great-recession-until-2018'> Maine has added jobs</a>. In October, Maine had an estimated 600,900 nonfarm jobs, an increase of more than 3,500 jobs since October 2012.</p>"
